 [[Stephen Cleobury]], 70, English organist, director of the [[Choir of King's College, Cambridge]], since 1982 <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kings.cam.ac.uk/news/2019/sir-stephen-cleobury-1948-2019 |title=Sir Stephen Cleobury (1948\u20132019) |accessdate=23 November 2019 |publisher=[[King's College, Cambridge]]}}</ref>\n* [[24 November]] \u2013 [[Colin Mawby]], 83, English organist, choral conductor and composer<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.cmc.ie/news/11252019-1330/colin-mawby-1936-2019| title = Colin Mawby (1936-2019)| website = The Contemporary Music Centre Ireland| date = 25 November 2019| accessdate = 25 November 2019}}</ref>\n* [[27 November]] \u2013 Sir [[Jonathan Miller]], British theatre and opera director, satirist, and physician, 85<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2019/nov/27/sir-jonathan-miller-obituary | title=Sir Jonathan Miller obituary | work=The Guardian | author=Michael Coveney | date=2019-11-27 | accessdate=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n* [[28 November]] \u2013 [[Christopher Finzi]], British conductor and son of [[Gerald Finzi]], 85\n* [[7 December]] \u2013 [[Simon Streatfeild]], 90, conductor and violist<ref>[https://www.therecord.com/whatson-story/9769270-simon-streatfeild-former-k-w-symphony-conductor-and-adviser-dies-at-90/ Simon Streatfeild, former K-W Symphony conductor and adviser, dies at 90]</ref>\n* [[29 December]] \n** Susanne Beer, German-born orchestral cellist resident in the United Kingdom and principal cello of the London Philharmonic Orchestra, 52<ref>{{cite web | url=https://jessicamusic.blogspot.com/2019/12/susanne-beer-31-october-1967-29.html | title=Susanne Beer, 31 October 1967 - 29 December 2019 | work=Jessica Duchen's Classical Music Blog | author=Jessica Duchen | date=2019-12-30 | accessdate=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n** [[Neil Innes]], 75, singer, musician, writer ([[Bonzo Dog Doo-Dah Band]]), ([[The Rutles]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/monty-python-musician-neil-innes-dies-aged-75-a4323151.html|title=Monty Python musician Neil Innes dies, aged 75|date=30 December 2019|website=Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2019 in British radio]]\n* [[2019 in British television]]\n* [[2019 in the United Kingdom]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Music of the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in British music| ]]\n[[Category:British music by year|2019]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also|Timeline of musical events}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Year in music|2019}}\n{{Year nav topic5|2019|British music}}\n{{2010s in music (UK)}}\nThis is a summary of the year '''2019 in [[Music of the United Kingdom|British music]]'''.\n\n==Events==\n*[[3 January]] \u2013 The [[Royal College of Organists]] announces Hans Fagius and Nicolas Kynaston as the recipients of the RCO Medal for 2019.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.rco.org.uk/news_displaystory.php?newsid=294 | title=RCO Medal awarded to distinguished musicians | publisher=Royal College of Organists | date=3 January 2019 | accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n*[[10 January]] \u2013 The [[Brodsky Quartet]] announces the appointment of Gina McCormack as its new violinist, to replace the departing Daniel Rowland.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.rhinegold.co.uk/classical_music/brodksy-quartet-announces-new-member/ | title=Brodsky Quartet announces new member | work=Classical Music Magazine | author=Lucy Thraves | date=10 January 2019 | accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n*[[17 January]] \u2013 The Ernst von Siemens Music Foundation announces [[Rebecca Saunders]] as the recipient of the Ernst von Siemens Musikpreis 2019, the second woman and the first female composer ever to be honoured with the award.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jan/17/british-composer-rebecca-saunders-wins-ernst-von-siemens-music-prize | title=British composer Rebecca Saunders wins Ernst von Siemens Music prize | work=The Guardian | author=Mark Brown | date=17 January 2019 | accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n*[[21 January]] \u2013 The [[Barbican Centre]], [[London Symphony Orchestra]], and [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]] jointly unveil initial designs for the proposed privately-funded centre for music in the City of London.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.chicagolandmusicaltheatre.com/former-general-manager-ashley-magnus-named-gm-of-chicago-opera-theater/ | title=First Concept Designs Released For London Centre For Music Project As Next Steps Announced | publisher=Barbican Centre | date=21 January 2019 | accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n*[[24 January]] \u2013 [[Tasmin Little]] announces her intention to retire from classical music performance in the summer of 2020.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestrad.com/news/tasmin-little-announces-retirement-from-the-concert-platform/8583.article | title=Tasmin Little announces retirement from the concert platform | work=The Strad | author= | date=25 January 2019 | accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n*[[25 January]]\n** The [[BBC Symphony Orchestra]] announces the appointment of [[Dalia Stasevska]] as its next principal guest conductor, the first woman to be named to the post and the second female conductor ever to be given a titled post with a BBC orchestra.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jan/25/dalia-stasevska-joins-bbc-symphony-orchestra-as-principal-guest-conductor | title=Dalia Stasevska joins BBC Symphony Orchestra as principal guest conductor | work=The Guardian | author=Imogen Tilden | date=25 January 2019 | accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n** The [[Ulster Orchestra]] announces the appointment of [[Daniele Rustioni]] as its next chief conductor, effective September 2019.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/ulster-orchestra-baton-handed-over-as-italian-is-named-new-conductor-37746126.html | title=Ulster Orchestra baton handed over as Italian is named new conductor | work=Belfast Telegraph | author=Alf McCreary | date=25 January 2019 | accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n** The city of [[Schw\u00e4bisch Gm\u00fcnd]] announces [[John Rutter]] as the recipient of the ''Preis der Europ\u00e4ischen Kirchenmusik 2019''.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.schwaebisch-gmuend.de/pressedetails/preis-der-europ\u00e4ischen-kirchenmusik-2019.html | title=John Rutter erh\u00e4lt den Preis der Europ\u00e4ischen Kirchenmusik 2019 | publisher=Schw\u00e4bisch Gm\u00fcnd | date=25 January 2019 | accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[20 February]] \u2013 Future Talent announces [[Sheku Kanneh-Mason]] as its newest Ambassador.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://futuretalent.org/news/sheku-kanneh-mason-joins-future-talent | title=Sheku Kanneh-Mason joins Future Talent | publisher=Future Talent | date=20 February 2019 | accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[4 March]] \u2013 Scala Radio, a new classical radio station, begins transmission.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/mar/04/simon-mayo-scala-radio-review-no-senseless-interference-here-classical-radio-bbc | title=Simon Mayo's Scala Radio review \u2013 no 'senseless interference' here | work=The Guardian | author=Mark Lawson | date=4 March 2019 | accessdate=16 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[8 March]] \n** A [[British Phonographic Industry]] report indicates that with respect to music provision, state schools have seen a 21% decrease over the past 5 years, compared to a net increase of 7% in independent schools during the same period.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/news-analysis/bpi-calls-on-government-to-tackle-growing-inequality-in-access-to-music-in-state-schools/ | title=BPI calls on Government to tackle growing inequality in access to music in state schoolsr | publisher=British Phonographic Industry | date=8 March 2019 | accessdate=16 March 2019}}</ref>\n** [[Birmingham Con