ham]], Nicola Killean, [[Gary Lightbody]] and [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] are each made an Officer of the Order of the British Empire.\n** [[Helen Grime]], [[Sheku Kanneh-Mason]], and Charles Kennard are each made a Member of the Order of the British Empire.\n\n==Television programmes==\n[[File:Jess_Glynne_(17579099972).jpg|150px|thumb|Jess Glynne]]\n*[[1 January]] \u2013 [[Jools' Annual Hootenanny]] features [[Marc Almond]], [[George Ezra]], [[Junior Giscombe]], [[Jess Glynne]] and others.<ref name=\"2018/19\">{{cite web |title=BBC Two - Jools' Annual Hootenanny, 2018/19 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0bx3bmn |website=BBC |accessdate=31 December 2018}}</ref>\n*[[24 February]] \u2013 ''Pappano's Greatest Arias'', presented by [[Antonio Pappano]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2019/09/soft-cell-say-hello-wave-goodbye|title=Soft Cell: Say Hello, Wave Goodbye|website=BBC Media Centre|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n*[[1 March]] \u2013 ''Say Hello, Wave Goodbye'', documentary about [[Soft Cell]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0002w72|title=Pappano's Greatest Arias|website=BBC Four|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n*[[14 April]] \u2013 ''Janet Baker in her own words'', documentary about [[Janet Baker]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/apr/14/rachmaninov-isle-of-the-dead-lpo-jurowski-review-preludes-gilburg-janet-baker-in-her-own-words-bbc4|title=Home listening: Rachmaninov big and small, and a night in with Janet Baker|author=Fiona Maddocks|website=The Guardian|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n*[[7 September]] \u2013 ''[[Strictly Come Dancing (series 17)|Strictly Come Dancing]]'' 2019 season, introducing new judge [[Motsi Mabuse]]. \n*[[12 October]] \n**''[[The X Factor: Celebrity]]''; competitors include [[Brendan Cole]], [[Martin Bashir]] and [[Hayley Hasselhoff]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/x-factor-celebrity-brendan-cole-ricki-lake-and-ben-foden-among-stars-revealed-for-full-line-up-11823548|title=X Factor: Celebrity - Brendan Cole, Ricki Lake and Ben Foden among stars revealed for full-line up|website=[[Sky News]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref> The series is won by [[Megan McKenna]], with [[Max and Harvey]] second and [[Jenny Ryan]] third.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/11/30/megan-mckenna-crowned-x-factor-celebrity-winner-epic-final-11247182/|title=X Factor: Celebrity crowns Megan McKenna winner after epic final show|last=Griffin|first=Louise|access-date=30 November 2019|website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]}}</ref>\n**''[[Mark Ronson]]: From the Heart'' (BBC4 documentary)\n*[[10 December]] \u2013 ''[[Lucy Worsley]]'s Christmas Carol Odyssey'' (BBC4 documentary)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000c5y4|title=BBC Four \u2013 Lucy Worsley's Christmas Carol Odyssey|website=BBC|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n== Artists and groups reformed ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2019}}\n*[[Doves (band)|Doves]]\n*[[The Futureheads]]\n*[[JLS]]\n*[[Lighthouse Family]]\n*[[McFly]]\n*[[Monaco (band)|Monaco]]\n*[[The Power Station (band)|The Power Station]]\n*[[Roxy Music]]\n*[[Sugababes]] (original line up)\n*[[Supergrass]]\n\n== Artists and groups disbanded ==\n*[[Arms Race (band)|Arms Race]]\n*[[Estrons]]\n*[[Mallory Knox]]\n*[[Otherkin]]\n*[[The Searchers (band)|The Searchers]]\n*[[Spandau Ballet]]\n*[[The Spook School]]\n*[[Superfood]]\n\n==Classical works==\n* [[Thomas Ad\u00e8s]] \u2013 Concerto for Piano and Orchestra<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/08/arts/music/piano-concertos-thomas-ades-john-adams.html | title=Two Coasts, Two Concertos: Ad\u00e8s and Adams Offer Piano Premieres | work=The New York Times | author=David Allen and Zachary Woolfe | date=8 March 2019 | accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Sally Beamish]] \u2013 ''Nine Fragments'' (for string quartet)<ref>[https://wigmore-hall.org.uk/whats-on/elias-